      {
         "id": "SECTION_prerequisites",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p><p><span id=\"htAmericaAbyaYalaMsg\"></span> (<htcite0>).</p><p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htChinaZhongguo\"></p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htJapanNipponNihonKoku\"></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "160fb48c-1711-491e-a1aa-e1257e7889af",
                     "text": "Porto-Gonçalves, Carlos Walter",
                     "page": "pp. 39-43",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nIn this text, we will present a new representation of the abacuses studied so far: the Soroban and the Suanpan (算盤). Therefore, we recommend reading the previous text (<htcite0>), for a better understanding of this text.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d7a249ed-cc2d-40e0-adec-ca3e9738e5d3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Grandes ordens com o Soroban e Suanpan (算盤)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the West, we currently use numbers whose values increase from right to left: the units are on the right and, as new digits are added, the values of the orders increase (<htcite0>).\n\nBut, as we have also seen, the indigenous peoples of *Abya Yala* (America) represent their numbers vertically, with the smaller numbers at the bottom and the larger numbers at the top (<htcite1>).\n\nWhen studying the abacuses so far, we have always represented numbers from right to left, as we generally do with our numbers. Based on what we have learned about the indigenous peoples of *Abya Yala*, let us reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b1a262fc-0148-489b-8b70-5266a85c1e67",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Famílias Numéricas (Parte II)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6fd2997b-caf1-4620-a58f-1140388ab8c1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Mudança de direção (Parte II)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Both there and here</b><br /><br />Could we represent numbers on the abacus, vertically, <i>Schyoty (счёты)</i>, in the same way that the indigenous peoples of <i>Abya Yala</i> (America) represent their numbers?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_history",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### History\n\nWhen studying the Soroban (算盤), we learned that it is a tool built in Japan (Nippon-koku or Nihon-koku, 日本国) (<hcite0>). However, as we saw next, it originated from another abacus, the Suanpan (算盤), developed in China (<htcite1>).\n\nThe relationship between the two is explicit by the way numbers are represented, in addition to the same characters used in writing. Regarding the Schyoty (счёты) abacus, presented in **Figure 1**, this relationship is not as evident",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "339c7ff5-8365-49bb-a1cd-ad5a13d5fd86",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Construindo para contar (Soroban, 算盤)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c3c69877-a92b-493c-b98a-5c1c6d5875f4",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Construindo para contar (Suanpan, 算盤)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"abacus\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('abacus', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Example of an abacus used in Russia. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fd0438ef-781b-498f-9f8d-fd7fbfb9c458",
                     "text": "British Museum",
                     "page": "Abacus",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Possible origins\n\nWhen studying the mathematical tools used in Russia, Alexei Volkov raises important points about how this instrument could have arrived in the country.\n\nAlthough there are citations indicating that the instrument was already present in Russia around <htdate0>, it is not possible to state that its origin is China (Zhōngguó, 中國) (<htcite0>).\n\nIn his work, Alexei Volkov also mentions that research such as Simonov's proposes that the abacus used in Russia could be even older, possibly dating back to the 13th century, according to the Gregorian calendar. However, this hypothesis seems unlikely (<htcite1>).\n\nDespite the difficulties of dating and even defining its origin, the Russian abacus brings some interesting features, which we will begin to study.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b4129ac9-9e33-493c-9e7e-b59fb306762f",
                     "text": "Volkov, A.",
                     "page": "pp. 301",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
